ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A colorless poisonous gas synthesized by the oxidation of methanol and used as an antiseptic, disinfectant, histologic fixative, and general-purpose chemical reagent for laboratory applications.  Formaldehyde is readily soluble in water and is commonly distributed as a 37% solution in water; formalin, a 10% solution of formaldehyde in water, is used as a disinfectant and to preserve biological specimens. Environmentally, formaldehyde may be found in the atmosphere, smoke from fires, automobile exhaust and cigarette smoke.  Small amounts are produced during normal metabolic processes in most organisms, including humans. (NCI04)

Concepts.definition: A colorless poisonous gas synthesized by the oxidation of methanol and used as an antiseptic, disinfectant, histologic fixative, and general-purpose chemical reagent for laboratory applications. Formaldehyde is readily soluble in water and is commonly distributed as a 37% solution in water; formalin, a 10% solution of formaldehyde in water, is used as a disinfectant and to preserve biological specimens. Environmentally, formaldehyde may be found in the atmosphere, smoke from fires, automobile exhaust and cigarette smoke. Small amounts are produced during normal metabolic processes in most organisms, including humans.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Used as a solvent and as an intermediate in chemical synthesis.  Component of deicing mixtures and preservatives. Toxic.

Concepts.definition: Used as a solvent and as an intermediate in chemical synthesis.  Component of deicing mixtures and preservatives. Toxic.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition:
An aqueous dilution of ethanol containing 70% ethanol by volume. Used as a disinfecting agent and as
a fixative.

Concepts.definition: An aqueous dilution of ethanol containing 70% ethanol by volume.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A liquid preservative for cytological materials, consisting of methanol and glacial acetic acid in an approximately 3:1 ratio. It is typically used on tissues to be paraffin-embedded and immunochemically stained and is useful for the preservation of nucleic acids in situ.

Concepts.definition: A liquid preservative for cytological materials, consisting of methanol, chloroform and glacial acetic acid in a 6:3:1 ratio. It is typically used on tissues to be paraffin-embedded and immunochemically stained and is useful for the preservation of nucleic acids in situ.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A methanol/polyethylene glycol-based fixative that is useful for preservation of DNA, RNA, and proteins. It is particularly useful for preservation of nucleic acids in situ.

Concepts.longName: Short PR Interval by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an abnormally short PR interval. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Trade name for an aqueous, non-toxic tissue storage reagent that rapidly permeates tissues to stabilize and protect cellular RNA.

Concepts.definition: Trade name for an aqueous, non-toxic tissue storage reagent that rapidly permeates tissues to stabilize and protect cellular RNA.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tissue fixative consisting of formaldehyde, glacial acetic acid, and picric acid. It provides particularly excellent preservation of nuclei and chromosomes.

Concepts.definition: A tissue fixative consisting of formaldehyde, glacial acetic acid, and picric acid. It provides particularly excellent preservation of nuclei and chromosomes.
